hen</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Gorard</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-9381-5991</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-000-22-2005-A"><gtr:id>A43CA694-E00A-4431-A26F-CA4534A6B815</gtr:id><gtr:title>Who is studying science? An analysis of patterns in the recruitment, training and employment of scientists.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-000-22-2005-A</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>More science is now being taught to more students at school than at any time in history. However, falling A-level science entries, the closure of several university science and mathematics departments, poor career opportunities and educational experiences and narrow skills development, all point to a crisis in education and training in the sciences. This ?science problem? both threatens the place of the UK as a knowledge-based economy and foreshadows an impending crisis in the provision of scientifically educated workers and scientifically literate citizens. Much of the focus of the ?science problem? has been on long-standing concerns about how science is taught in schools. Less attention has been devoted to the undergraduate student experience and the reasons learners give for continuing along a career trajectory that will end in them becoming professional scientists and technicians. In this project we will combine secondary data analysis with a survey and interviews with undergraduate students, to examine these three research questions:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>What are the long-term patterns of participation in science and science-related courses at the end of compulsory schooling?&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>What influences undergraduate students? decisions to pursue a career in science? &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>What happens to science graduates once they leave higher education?&lt;/li>
